Reference-contexts: 1 Introduction Given an undirected graph G = (V; E), a k-coloring of G consists of assigning an integer in the range <ref> [1; k] </ref> to each vertex v 2 V . A valid k-coloring of G is a k-coloring for which no two adjacent vertices are assigned the same integer. Determining the smallest k for which there is a valid k-coloring of G is N P-hard.
